{
  "texts": [
    "This can be seen in the 3.0 GeV Au+Au collision results shown in Fig. 14.",
    "The early strong partonic expansion leads to positive v 2 with NCQ scaling in high-energy collisions, whereas at 3.0 GeV, both weaker pressure gradients and shadowing of the spectators result in negative v 2 values without scaling.",
    "The results from calculations using the hadronic transport models JAM and UrQMD are also shown as colored bands in the figure.",
    "By including the baryonic mean field, both the JAM and UrQMD models reproduce the trends for both dv 1 ∕dy| y=0 and v 2 for baryons, including protons and Λ.",
    "The consist- ency of the transport models (JAM and UrQMD) with the baryonic mean field for all measured baryons implies that the dominant degrees of freedom at a collision energy of 3.0 GeV are from the interacting baryons."
  ]
}